N:langextract
D:LLM-powered structured information extraction from unstructured text with character-level source grounding (provenance). Every extracted entity maps back to exact character offsets. Use when extracting entities, relationships, or structured data from documents. Supports Gemini (default), OpenAI, Ollama, and custom providers via plugin.
G:langextract information-extraction nlp ner entity-extraction structured-output gemini openai ollama grounding provenance document-parsing text-mining

U[7]:
  Extract named entities with character-level provenance from any text document
  Process clinical notes, legal documents, or research papers into structured data
  Build schema-enforced extraction pipelines without fine-tuning using few-shot examples
  Handle long documents (100k+ chars) with chunking, parallel workers, and multi-pass extraction
  Generate interactive HTML visualizations of annotated source text
  Run local/private extraction with Ollama (no API key required)
  Extend with custom LLM providers via Python entry-point plugin system

S[6]{n,action,details}:
  1,Install,pip install langextract (Gemini default) or pip install langextract[openai] for OpenAI support; set LANGEXTRACT_API_KEY env var
  2,Define schema,Create ExampleData objects with few-shot examples showing extraction_class + extraction_text + attributes — schema is inferred automatically, no fine-tuning needed
  3,Extract,Call lx.extract(text_or_documents=..., prompt_description=..., examples=..., model_id="gemini-2.5-flash") — returns result with .extractions list
  4,Long docs,Add extraction_passes=3 (multi-pass merge) + max_workers=20 (parallel chunks) + max_char_buffer=1000 for 100k+ character documents
  5,Visualize,lx.io.save_annotated_documents([result], output_name="results.jsonl"); html = lx.visualize("results.jsonl") → color-coded annotation viewer
  6,Verify,result.text[extraction.start:extraction.end] must equal extraction.extraction_text — use this assertion to catch offset drift

R[5]:
  Write precise prompts: "use exact text, do not paraphrase" keeps character offsets accurate
  Use 2-3 few-shot ExampleData covering edge cases — quality of examples drives extraction quality
  For long documents set extraction_passes=3 to catch entities missed in a single pass
  Use max_char_buffer=500-1000 for focused context windows; larger values reduce API calls but may miss entities
  Use fence_output=True and use_schema_constraints=False for OpenAI/Ollama (only Gemini supports controlled generation)

E[4]{desc,in,out}:
  "Basic entity extraction","lx.extract(text='Patient took 10mg aspirin daily', prompt_description='Extract medications and dosages', examples=[...], model_id='gemini-2.5-flash')","Extraction(extraction_class='medication', extraction_text='aspirin', start=16, end=23, attributes={'dosage': '10mg', 'frequency': 'daily'})"
  "Long document from URL","lx.extract(text_or_documents='https://gutenberg.org/files/1513/1513-0.txt', ..., extraction_passes=3, max_workers=20)","4088 entities extracted from Romeo & Juliet (147k chars) — characters, emotions, relationships with offsets"
  "Local LLM via Ollama","lx.extract(..., model_id='gemma2:2b', model_url='http://localhost:11434', fence_output=False, use_schema_constraints=False)","Same extraction interface with fully local model — no API key or internet required"
  "HTML visualization","lx.io.save_annotated_documents([result], 'results.jsonl'); html = lx.visualize('results.jsonl')","Self-contained HTML file with color-coded entity annotations overlaid on source text"
